Every network device has a unique MAC address, with the first 6 characters (OUI - Organizationally Unique Identifier) assigned to specific manufacturers. A Media Access Control (MAC) address is a unique identifier assigned to a network interface controller (NIC) for use as a network address in communications within a network segment. What is an OUI in MAC addresses? It's the first 24 bits (3 bytes) of a MAC address that identifies the manufacturer or vendor of a network interface.
